# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-party-cyprus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2014-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Cyprus's component of the 2014 European Parliament election was held on Sunday, 25 May 2014.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2014-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] In total, 6 Members of the European Parliament were elected from Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2014-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] There were also eight independent candidates.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Cyprus on 22 May 2016 to elect 56 of the 80 Members of the House of Representatives.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The Republic of Cyprus is a unitary republic with a presidential system of government.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The President of Cyprus, directly elected in the middle of the legislative term, is both head of state and head of government, presiding over the executive Council of Ministers.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The 80 seats in the House of Representatives are elected from six multi-member constituencies, with the number of seats allocated according to the population of each area.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Of the 80 seats, 56 are elected by Greek Cypriots and 24 by Turkish Cypriots.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] However, due to the partition of the island in 1974, the 24 Turkish Cypriot seats are unfilled and the House of Representatives has de facto had 56 seats since its enlargement in the 1980s.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The elections are held using open list proportional representation, with seats allocated using the Hare quota.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Any remaining seats are allocated to lists that won at least one seat or parties that received at least 3.6% of the vote.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] In the open list system, voters first select the list they want to vote for, and then select a number of candidates equal to a quarter of the number of seats in the constituency.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Party leaders or other candidates heading coalitions are not required to receive preferential votes to be elected.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Although compulsory voting had not been formally abolished at the time the elections took place (it was abolished in 2017), the law had not been enforced for years.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The previous legislative election took place on 22 May 2011.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] President Demetris Christofias of the communist Progressive Party of Working People (AKEL) had led a coalition consisting of his party as well as the centrist Democratic Party (DIKO) and the social-democratic Movement for Social Democracy (EDEK) since his election in 2008.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] After three years in power, AKEL scored 32.7% in the 2011 legislative elections, narrowly behind the opposition center-right Democratic Rally, which polled 34.3% of votes.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Meanwhile, AKEL's partners DIKO and EDEK scored 15.8% and 8.9% respectively.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] A mere two months after the legislative election, the Evangelos Florakis Naval Base explosion took place, triggering calls for President Christofias' resignation.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Amidst widespread dissatisfaction and a deepening economic crisis, Christofias announced that he would not run for a second term in the presidential election in 2013.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Ultimately, Nicos Anastasiades of DISY emerged victorious in the presidential election, taking 45.5% of the vote, against 26.9% for the AKEL-backed Stavros Malas and the EDEK-backed Giorgos Lillikas.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] In the second round, Anastasiades captured 57.5% to 42.5% for Malas.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The Anastasiades administration took office on 28 February 2013, comprising DISY, DIKO and the European Party (EVROKO).
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The Democrats later pulled out of the coalition, however.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Roughly a year into the presidency of Nicos Anastasiades, the Cypriot parties faced the electorate in European Parliament elections.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Ahead of the election, DISY and EVROKO announced that they would participate in the election on a joint ticket; the social democrats in EDEK and the Ecological and Environmental Movement (KOP) also formed an electoral pact for the event.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] With the economic problems the country faced under Demetris Christofias' AKEL-led government fresh in the minds of voters, the party plummeted to 27.0% of the vote, a loss of 8.4% points.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Meanwhile, the DISY-EVROKO pact garnered 37.8%.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] This election also served as the first electoral test of the Citizens' Alliance (SYPOL) party of former presidential candidate Giorgos Lillikas, which polled 6.8% but failed to win seats in the European Parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The decline of AKEL and the rise of anti-establishment parties continued into 2015 and 2016.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Mere months before the 2016 legislative election, ex-DISY MEP Eleni Theocharous launched a splinter party, in opposition to Anastasiades' approach to the Cyprus issue.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] She advocated for tighter co-operation with other parties particularly DIKO and EDEK.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The new party was dubbed the Solidarity Movement.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] On 11 March 2016, it was announced that EVROKO would merge into the new party, placing its candidates on its lists in the upcoming elections.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] A televised debate of DISY leader Averof Neophytou, AKEL leader Andros Kyprianou and DIKO leader Nicolas Papadopoulos on 18 May 2016 turned into a heated exchange on economy issues and the question of reunification.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Papadopoulos claimed that "behind closed doors", AKEL was trying to resurrect the 2004 Annan plan that was turned down by the Greek side in a referendum.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] While Neophytou and Papadopoulos criticized AKEL's judgment of the economic situation ahead of the 2012–13 Cypriot financial crisis, Kyprianou recalled his two rivals' assessments at that time.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The election had the lowest turnout for a legislative election in the history of the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] AKEL was seen as the biggest loser of the election, possible reasons being cited as the party's failure to take up a "proactive" role and continued disillusionment with the Christofias administration.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] In contrast, an AKEL member, Irini Charalambidou, gained the highest number of votes for any candidate, following her stark critique of and fight against failing banks.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] The results were interpreted as a weakening of the front calling for a federal solution by the Turkish Cypriot press and political analyst Louis Igoumenides.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] In terms of economics, the Anastasiades government became dependent on smaller parties to pass important reforms.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] This was expected to impede the ability of the government to pass these reforms, economic analyst Fiona Mullen said "I think we can forget privatization altogether".
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] This was also the first time the far-right party ELAM entered the parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2016-cypriot-legislative-election] Cypriot electoral expert Yiannis Mavris said: "The electoral results herald a new political era for Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2019-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] An election was held on 26 May 2019 to elect six representatives from Cyprus to the European Parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2019-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The Democratic Rally (DISY) has won every election to the European Parliament since Cyprus joined the European Union in 2004.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2019-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] According to final results, DISY again won the election with 29% and 2 seats.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2019-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] There were no changes in seat allocation, with AKEL also at 2 seats after securing 27% of the vote.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2019-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] DIKO and EDEK had 1 seat each, with 14% and 11% of the vote, respectively.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2019-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] In terms of percentage, this was EDEK's best European elections result since 2004 (although that year it did not win any seats).
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2019-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Some attributed this in part to tactical voting, with many fearing the far-right ELAM gaining a seat had it finished fourth.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2021-cypriot-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Cyprus on 30 May 2021 to elect 56 of the 80 Members of the House of Representatives.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2021-cypriot-legislative-election] The 80 members of the House of Representatives are elected from six multi-member constituencies, with the number of seats allocated according to the population of each area.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2021-cypriot-legislative-election] Of the 80, 56 are elected by Greek Cypriots and 24 by Turkish Cypriots.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2021-cypriot-legislative-election] However, since 1964, the Turkish Cypriot seats are unfilled and the House of Representatives has de facto had 56 seats since its enlargement in the 1980s.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2021-cypriot-legislative-election] Each constituency corresponds to the six districts of Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2021-cypriot-legislative-election] Seats are allocated using the Hare quota, with any remaining seats allocated to lists that won at least one seat or parties that received at least 3.6% of the vote.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2021-cypriot-legislative-election] Anti-government demonstrations have been taking place that resulted in clashes with the police.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2021-cypriot-legislative-election] Despite the COVID-19 pandemic in Cyprus, the campaign and voting process is not expected to be significantly altered.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The **2024 European Parliament elections** in Cyprus was held on 9 June 2024 as part of the 2024 European Parliament election.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] This was the fifth parliamentary election since Cyprus's EU accession in 2004.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The centre-right Democratic Rally (DISY), which has won every previous election to this body, emerged victorious again with 24.8% of the votes, securing 2 seats.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The communist party AKEL followed with 21.5% and 1 seat.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Independent candidate Fidias Panayiotou, a well-known YouTuber and TikToker, finished third with 19.4% of the votes, earning one seat in the European Parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Panayiotou had no support from any party, making him the first elected independent MEP in the history of Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] His election sent shockwaves through the Cypriot political system, with Fidias finishing within several percentage points behind AKEL and DISY, which have dominated the Cypriot political system since independence.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The 24-year-old YouTuber, with no political experience, gained a seat at the expense of well-established parties like ELAM, DIKO and EDEK.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] To reduce costs, the election was held concurrently with the municipal elections.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Voters were provided with six different ballots.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] This was the first such vote to take place since the withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the European Union.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Also known as 'Brexit', the move impacted Cyprus due to ties linked to its status as a fellow Commonwealth member and former UK colony.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The election was primarily focused on the issue of illegal migration, with President Nikos Christodoulides declaring that Cyprus is in "a state of serious crisis".
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Due to the Gaza war, the number of illegal migrants in Cyprus skyrocketed, with more than 2,000 people arriving in the first three months of 2024, compared to just 78 in the same period the previous year.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] According to the president, 7% of the Cypriot population now consists of migrants.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] This increasing migrational upheaval led to a significant rise in the poll numbers of the far-right, anti-immigration party ELAM, whose manifesto is primarily focused on illegal migration.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The independent candidacy of 24-year-old YouTuber and TikToker Fidias Panayiotou was initially viewed as a joke and was ignored by political parties.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Panayiotou was open about his lack of political knowledge and did not express any concrete political positions.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] However, his adept use of social media successfully crafted his image as the main anti-establishment and anti-partisan candidate.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] His name appeared in opinion polls just one month before the election, showing single-digit voting intentions and zero seat projections.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] This election was the European Parliament election with the highest number of Turkish Cypriot candidates from different parties.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The incumbent Member of the Parliament Niyazi Kizilyurek was running again with AKEL, the new founded party Volt Cyprus was showing Hulusi Kilim as a lead candidate, and Oz Karahan was running as a candidate from KOSP.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The government also started campaigns for including the Turkish Cypriots more into the elections.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The Democratic Rally (DISY) has won every election since the island's accession into the EU in 2004, though the party recently suffered defeat in the presidential election.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Nine DISY personalities announced their interest for the European Parliament Elections.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The six nominees were selected through an internal election process, with former Health Minister Michalis Hatzipantelas emerging as the top candidate.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Marios Pelekanos, one of the three vice presidents of the Democratic Rally, finished second to last in the internal election and was not included in the list of six nominees.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Pelekanos expressed profound dissatisfaction and subsequently resigned from his position within the party leadership, citing a series of underlying events that had undermined his standing.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] After multi-day discussions with ELAM, on March 22, 2024, it was announced that he would run in the European Elections as a candidate of the ultranationalist party.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The leader of the Democratic Rally, Annita Demetriou, harshly condemned this move, and the center-right party proceeded by deleting Pelekanos from its registry, emphasising the vast differences in politics between the two parties.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] However, the 24.8% of the popular vote is the worst result in the party's history, significantly lower than the 29% in the 2019 election and the 37.8% in the 2014 election.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Anna Theologou, leader of the centre-left party Generation Change, is featured as one of AKEL's candidates, effectively merging the two parties.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Theologou is regarded as a highly reputable politician, with the ability to attract votes to the communist party based on her personal influence.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] After consistently placing second in every European Parliament Election, some opinion polls indicated a surge in the party's performance relative to the frontrunner DISY, with some polls even positioning it in the first place.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Moreover, the opinion polls did not include Turkish Cypriot voters, although they have the right to vote.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Since AKEL's candidates included the Turkish Cypriot Niyazi Kizilyurek, the Turkish Cypriot vote was expected to boost the percentage for the left-wing party even more.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Despite these expectations, AKEL experienced its worst defeat in its history, receiving just 21.5% of the votes, only 2 percentage points ahead of independent candidate and YouTuber Fidias Panayiotou.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The party lost one of its two seats and now, for the first time in its history, holds only one seat in the European Parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The far-right party ELAM was projected by all opinion polls to secure its first seat in the European Parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Formerly considered on the fringe, the party was now anticipated to achieve a third-place finish, surpassing DIKO, with every poll indicating a percentage higher than 13%.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Known for its anti-establishment and often labeled extremist positions, the party was now being considered "mainstream" for the first time, as illegal migration became the most important issue for Cypriot voters.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The party announced the candidacy of Pavlos Ioannou, who served as the financial commissioner of Cyprus from 2013 to 2023.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The candidacy of the reputable figure caused surprise and was anticipated to attract more moderate voters to the party often referred to as "extremist".
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Notably, Ioannou clarified that he is not a member of ELAM but has been granted complete freedom of speech and disagreement by the party.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] He emphasized that his views align more with rationalism rather than far-right ideologies.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Additionally, Ioannou stated his commitment not to vote against the rights of the LGBTQ+ community in potential European votes, provided that the rights of other groups were not impeded.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The announcement of Marios Pelekanos' candidacy with ELAM, who had been serving as vice president of the centre-right DISY until a few weeks prior, created a political upheaval.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Pelekanos, who also held the position of government spokesperson in Anastasiades' administration from 2021 to 2023, was believed to have the potential to attract a considerable number of DISY voters to ELAM.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The party did succeed in securing its first seat, winning 3 percentage points more than in 2019, but the "Fidias Phenomenon" likely hindered its rising momentum, with the vote share of 11.2% being lower than what most opinion polls predicted.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Despite finishing third in all previous European elections, the Democratic Party (DIKO) now appeared fourth in every opinion poll released, falling below the far-right ELAM.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The party's candidates featured the veteran politician and paediatric surgeon Eleni Theocharous, who had served as an MEP from 2009 to 2019 initially with DISY and later with the newly established Solidarity Movement.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The conservative politician, who was ranked 3 times as the second best MEP by the DEVE Committee, was widely considered a strong candidate to attract nationalist voters away from ELAM.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The list also featured biochemist Leondios Kostrikis, who served as a member of the Advisory Committee of the Ministry of Health during the COVID-19 pandemic in Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The Professor is also internationally known for his discovery of a new COVID-19 variant in January 2022, the so-called "Deltacron", at the University of Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The historic party, which had consistently finished third in every legislative and European election in Cyprus since its foundation in 1976, suffered a significant defeat.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The vote share of 9.7% marked the first single-digit result in the party's history, and the fifth-place finish was its lowest ranking.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The well-established party, with tens of thousands of members, received 10 percentage points less than the 24-year-old YouTuber Fidias Panayiotou, who ran as an independent candidate with no political experience.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Despite this setback, DIKO managed to retain its seat, re-electing incumbent MEP Costas Mavrides.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] According to all opinion polls, the centre-left party EDEK was projected to lose its seat in the European Parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Critics accused the party of losing its identity, with some even claiming that many of its political positions became indistinguishable from those of the far-right party ELAM.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] EDEK received 5.1% of the popular vote, marking the lowest percentage in its 55-year history.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The "traditional 4th-place party" lost its seat in the European Parliament (which it had consistently secured since 2009) and finished 6th, marking its lowest place in history.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] After the merge of its alliance party SYPOL with EDEK in 2021, the green party KOSP cooperated with Echmi Movement and Union of Cypriots for the 2024 European Election.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] In October 2023, Alexandra Attalides, one of the three elected KOSP MPs, resigned from the party.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] She cited dissatisfaction with the party's stance on the Cyprus problem, its inability to produce concrete and comprehensive policy proposals, and the vindictive behaviour of its collective members.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Attalides also accused the party of diverging from the policies, principles, and values of the European Greens, promoting xenophobia, and failing to oppose large-scale developments that harm the environment.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] In November 2023, Alexandra Attalides announced her membership in the newly established Volt Cyprus, and the following month, she was elected as the party's president.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The day after Alexandra Attalides' shocking resignation and her serious accusations, the president of KOSP, Charalambos Theopemptou, resigned from his position.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Following an internal election, the presidency returned to George Perdikes, who had previously served as the party's president from 2014 to 2020.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Following Alexandra Attalides' resignation, more resignations ensued, including 16 of the 67 members of the Central Committee.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Efi Xanthou, a 2019 candidate for the European Parliament and George Perdikes' opponent in the internal election after Charalambos Theopemptou's resignation, left the party in May 2024, accusing it of making undemocratic decisions.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] On March 21, 2024, Fidias Panayiotou, a globally renowned Cypriot YouTuber, confirmed speculations that he was approached by the KOSP to be included in their list of six candidates for the European elections.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Panayiotou engaged his audience by conducting a poll on TikTok to gauge their opinion on his potential candidacy, offering two options: running as a member of KOSP or running independently.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Out of a total of 10,000 participants, 70% favored the latter option.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Consequently, Panayiotou announced his decision to pursue an independent candidacy.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] After facing numerous challenges and resignations, the party received its worst result since 2001, garnering just 1.3% of the popular vote and failing to secure any seats.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] This marked a significant decline from the 3.29% achieved in the 2019 European election, leaving the party with only one-third of its previous political power.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] On October 26, 2023, the New Wave and Famagusta for Cyprus movements announced their merger, resulting in the formation of Volt Cyprus as a political party.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The Cyprus branch of Volt Europa was officially established on December 3, 2023, shortly after the resignation of MP Alexandra Attalides from KOSP.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Alexandra Attalides, who received the 2021 "International Anti-Corruption Champions Award" from the United States, was elected as the party's president.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Attalides prioritised addressing climate change, corruption, the Cyprus problem, the rise of the far-right, and immigration as the main focuses for the party.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The party's candidates for the European Elections include Makarios Drousiotis, a political activist, journalist, and writer.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Drousiotis had garnered significant attention following the publication of a trilogy of books containing personal accounts and third-party documents uncovering extensive corruption scandals during the presidency of Nicos Anastasiades.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] His third publication, "Mafia State," instigated a criminal investigation against Anastasiades, prompting the involvement of international legal practitioner Gabrielle Louise McIntyre.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Despite being a newcomer, the party received 2.9% of the votes, surpassing KOSP and DIPA, both of which hold seats in the House of Representatives.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Makarios Drousiotis received the most votes among the six candidates of Volt Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] However, the party did not secure any seats.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Pantelis Poietis, formerly the Deputy Secretary of International Relations of the Democratic Rally (DISY), is now one of the six candidates nominated by DIPA for the European Elections.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] After resigning from DISY on September 9, 2022, Poietis supported Nicos Christodoulides in the 2023 Presidential Election, who stood as an opposing candidate to DISY's Averof Neofytou.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Fidias Panayiotou, a 24-year-old YouTuber, turned down an offer to join the Ecologists' electoral list and instead announced his independent candidacy for this election.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] He initiated a social media campaign with the goal of increasing youth voter registration.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] On 30 March 2024, he live-streamed himself on YouTube running 80 km from Kyrenia to Larnaca to encourage young people to register for the election.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] On that day alone, over 2000 new voter registrations were recorded.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] He also launched a podcast series, interviewing renowned political and non-political personalities, to engage both himself and his audience in political discussions.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] His candidacy was initially widely viewed as a joke and not perceived as a threat by political parties.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The fact that no independent candidate had ever come close to being elected as an MEP in the history of Cyprus combined with his political illiteracy, made Panayiotou an outsider.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] It wasn't until one month before the election that his name started appearing in opinion polls, and even then, with single-digit voting intentions.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The sudden increase in Fidias' percentages was dubbed the "Fidias Phenomenon," highlighting how an independent candidate with no political experience could shake up the Cypriot political system.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Fidias ran on an anti-partisan and anti-establishment platform, accusing establishment politicians of neglecting society's best interests and failing to understand critical modern developments such as AI and Bitcoin.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] He emphasised education as a priority, aiming to enhance schools in both Cyprus and the EU by eliminating exams and promoting self-education.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] He also acknowledged the significance of adapting to the impact of artificial intelligence on future developments.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Regarding the Cyprus issue, Panayiotou leaned towards the "Bi-zonal, Bi-communal Federation" solution while expressing a willingness to learn more about the complexities involved.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Additionally, he advocated for a measured approach to migration, proposing that asylum applications should be processed from applicants' home countries before their arrival in Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Fidias' electoral success was attributed to his adept use of social media and the widespread dissatisfaction of the public with the current political system.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Without spending any money on TV advertisements, billboards, or Google ads, he crafted his image as the primary anti-establishment candidate purely through daily, non-sponsored YouTube shorts.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Some journalists described this as Cyprus entering an era of "metapolitics," where protest votes were able to elect an "apolitical," independent candidate.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The unprecedented result of 19.4% was just 2 percentage points lower than the left-wing AKEL, a party with nearly 100 years of history that, along with DISY, has dominated the Cypriot political system since the country's independence.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The third-place finish of the independent candidate sent shockwaves through the Cypriot political system, with the well-established DIKO, traditionally the third-place party, receiving 10 percentage points less than him.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Fidias also surpassed the far-right ELAM, which had been anticipated to thrive due to the recent surge in illegal migration.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Following his election as an MEP, Fidias announced plans to create a new European political party with other like-minded MEPs.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] He also expressed interest in joining the Education Committee of the EU and suggested the creation of a new Social Media and AI Committee.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] Along with Luxembourg and Malta, Cyprus is the smallest constituency, electing 6 Members of the European Parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/2024-european-parliament-election-in-cyprus] The seats are distributed via open list proportional representation.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/action-cypriot-political-party] The alliance's electoral slate comprised 4 Greek Cypriots and 2 Turkish Cypriots.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/action-cypriot-political-party] Some commentators saw Action's low vote as a reflection of a deep-rooted division of the two communities.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/action-cypriot-political-party] The Friedrich Ebert Foundation considered it the result of a failure to sufficiently distinguish itself from AKEL and to overcome that party's historical organisational advantage.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] The **ALMA – Citizens for Cyprus** (Greek: ΑΛΜΑ – Πολίτες για την Κύπρο, romanized: *ALMA – Polítes gia tin Kýpro*, lit.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] 'Leap') is a centrist political party in Cyprus founded in 2025 by former Auditor General Odysseas Michaelides.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] On 18 September 2024, Odysseas Michaelides was dismissed from his position as Auditor General by Supreme Constitutional Court on charges of misconduct.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] Michaelides held the post for 10 years and became a controversial figure in Cypriot politics, repeatedly clashing with government officials.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] Michaelides himself accused ex-President Nicos Anastasiades and current President Nikos Christodoulides of staying behind his removal.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] Michaelides' resignation was criticized by Cypriot parties such as AKEL, KOSP, DIKO, and Volt, who characterized him as an official who exposed corruption and advocated for transparency.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] Several months after his removal, on 19 May 2025, Michaelides launched his party, ALMA – Citizens for Cyprus.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] It was established to contest the 2026 Cypriot legislative election and has presented itself as a long-term reform movement.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] The party's name, which translates as "leap," is also an acronym for Greek words meaning Dignity, Accountability, Reform, and Development.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] At the party's launch in Nicosia, Michaelides was accompanied by eight of his associates, including former Rector of the University of Cyprus Constantinos Christofides, who ran in the 2023 presidential election and finished sixth with 1.59% of the vote.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] The party describes itself as belonging to the “reformist centre”, promoting institutional reform, transparency, accountability, the rule of law, a socially responsible but competitive economy, participatory democracy, and strong protection of human rights.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] Its ideology can therefore be broadly characterised as centrist, reformist, socially liberal, pro-rule of law, and anti-corruption.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/alma-citizens-for-cyprus] The party was described by Europe Elects as centrist.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/animal-party-cyprus] The **Animal Party Cyprus** (**APC**, Greek: Κόμμα για τα Ζώα Κύπρου, Turkish: *Kıbrıs Hayvan Partisi*) is a political party in Cyprus advocating for animal rights and welfare.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/animal-party-cyprus] It was founded on 27 April 2014, and is led by Kyriakos Kyriakou.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/animal-party-cyprus] The party is one of the seven founding members of the European group Animal Politics EU, which is affiliated with The Left in the European Parliament.
[src:animal-party-cyprus/animal-party-cyprus] APC is a "hardcore" (single-issue) party and as such forms a core of the group.
